<subsection><title> Summary </title>

	<p>
		In this chapter, we explored first-order differential equations and the methods for solving them. Whether you're using direct integration, separation of variables, or the integrating factor method, these tools provide systematic approaches to tackle a wide range of problems. The following outline serves as a quick reference to the key concepts and terminology introduced, helping you consolidate your understanding and application of these techniques.
	</p>

	<aside>
		<p>
			ℹ️ Clicking on <c>A4</c> or <c>US</c> will open a printer-friendly version of this resource.
		</p>
	</aside>

	<worksheet><title> Key Terms &amp; Concepts </title>

		<p>
			<assemblage><title> First-Order Differential Equations </title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li xml:id="summary-first-order-de"><title> First-Order Differential Equation </title>
							<p>
								Every first-order differential equation can be written in the form 
								<me>
									\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x, y).
								</me>
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</p>

		<p>
			<assemblage><title> Separation of Variables </title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li xml:id="summary-separable-de"><title> First-Order Separable Differential Equation </title>
							<p>
								These equations can be written as:
								<me>
									\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y).
								</me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="summary-sov"><title> Separation of Variables Method </title>
							<p>
								A solution technique for separable equations. It involves isolating <m>y</m> and <m>x</m> terms on opposite sides, followed by integration.
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</p>

		<p>
			<assemblage><title> Integrating Factor </title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li xml:id="summary-first-order-linear-de"><title> First-Order Linear Differential Equation </title>
							<p>
								These equations take the standard form:
								<me>
									y' + P(x)y = Q(x).
								</me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="summary-integrating-factor"><title> Integrating Factor </title>
							<p>
								A function, <m>\mu</m>, multiplied onto the standard form, above, to reverse the product rule, leading to the equation, <m>\mu' = P\mu</m>, with the solution
								<me>
									\mu = e^{\int P(x) dx}.
								</me>
							</p>
						</li>
						<li xml:id="summary-method"><title> Integrating Factor Method </title>
							<p>
								A solution method for first-order linear equations that uses an integrating factor to convert the equation into a form solvable by direct integration.
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</p>

	</worksheet>


</subsection>